AGI -&nbsp;Qatar, Egypt and the United States have asked Israel and Hamas to accept the agreement illustrated by the White House and which provides for the release of hostages and the ceasefire. " Qatar, the United States and Egypt jointly demand both Hamas and Israel to finalize the agreement that incorporates the principles outlined by President Biden on 31 May 2024," reads in a joint statement, "an agreement that serves multiple interests and will bring immediate relief to both the people of Gaza who have long suffered, both the hostages and their families." "This agreement offers a roadmap for a ceasefire and the end of the crisis", adds the statement, relaunched by the Times of Israel.&nbsp; In response to the proposal by Biden, an Israeli official told the Times of Israel that "the conditions of Israel for the end of the war have not changed >: destroy the military and civilian capacities of Hamas, free the hostages and ensure that Gaza no longer represents a threat to Israel." The Israeli proposal, the official insists, guarantees that the Jewish state can carry out all these conditions before a permanent ceasefire enters into force and will ensure the release of all 125 hostages, > starting with a "humanitarian phase" in which women, children, sick and elderly will be released. This first phase will see a temporary pause in the fights, as well as talks to get the release of the remaining live and killed hostages and a permanent ceasefire.
&nbsp;
The second stage will take place only after Israel has received assurances on the terms of ceasefire and the Jewish state reserves the right to resume hostilities at any time if Hamas violates the terms of the agreement, "including the failure to issue the agreed number of hostages or if he considers that the talks are futile and are aimed only to take time." Meanwhile, thousands of Israelis marched through the centre of Jerusalem to the presidential residence, urging the government to accept the agreement. The protesters inhale thanksgiving signs to Biden and many wave yellow flags, symbol of the hostages held by Hamas in Gaza. Although the march was originally planned as an anti-government protest focused on the upcoming Jerusalem Day party, the organizers changed the theme in what seems a decisive moment for a potential deal. At the head of the parade some relatives of the hostages.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<h2> The Washington line
Hamas is warmly invited by the President of the United States himself, Joe Biden, to accept a new proposal for agreement > in three stages put on the table by Israel, because "it is time for this war to end." The head of the White House announced it by surprise, in a speech in which he outlined a possible solution to the conflict, in course for almost 8 months. The proposal, explained the same president, previews a first phase of six weeks in which the Israeli armed forces would withdraw from all the inhabited areas of the Gaza Strip >, and hoped that it will start "after tomorrow". "It is a decisive moment, we cannot lose it - said Biden - After an intense diplomatic activity, carried out by my team, in conversations with the leaders of Israel, Qatar, Egypt and other countries of the Middle East, Israel offered a new global proposal for a ceasefire and the release of all hostages," he said. In his speech, Biden insisted that the proposal, already sent to Hamas through Qatar, is also favourable for Hamas. In the first phase, he said, there would be a complete ceasefire for 6 weeks, during which Israeli troops would retreat from all the populated areas of the Strip and several hostages would be released, including women, elderly and wounded, in exchange for the release of hundreds of Palestinian prisoners.
&nbsp;
During these six weeks, Israel and Hamas should negotiate the details of the second phase, which would imply "the final end of hostility", the release of the rest of the hostages, including soldiers, and the withdrawal of the Israeli army from the Strip. According to Biden, this second phase will require very intense negotiations, and the ceasefire should not be violated > until they continue. The third and final phase would provide a "great reconstruction plan" for the Palestinian enclave and the return of the bodies of the murdered hostages. "If Hamas maintains its commitments, the temporary ceasefire will be transformed, according to the text of the Israeli proposal, into a permanent cessation of hostilities", added <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-05-30/ucraina-biden-autorizza-uso-armi-colpire-russia-26588420/"Bi> "This is the offer that is now on the table. That is what we ask and what we need," said Biden. Hamas has on several occasions reiterated that for any agreement the permanent truce and complete Israeli retreat "are not negotiable". Biden did not talk about the situation in Rafah, but he defined "a hell" > how much the Palestinian population is endured, adding that it only has to gain from the acceptance of the proposal.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<h2>Hamas: "Positive Biden's speech"</h2>
Hamas claims to "consider positively" the Israeli roadmap towards a ceasefire announced by US President Joe Biden after almost eight months of war in Gaza.<br> "Hamas considers positive" the contents of Biden's speech today about "a ceasefire, the withdrawal of Israeli forces from Gaza, reconstruction and exchange of prisoners", said the Palestinian Islamic movement in a statement.
&nbsp;

